Text.Value: I'll not deny he wounded me. I cared for Wulbren - care for him, really. But he's... well, he's acting like a true idiot.
There you are. I was wondering where the devil you'd been.
That is to say, they gabbed about their plans like geese, and I overheard them, like a very devious goose.
What about him?
Farewell. And good luck.
To talk about Wulbren, of course.
My friend. Yes. He'll always be my friend, won't he? And I - I believe I'll think of him every day.
Because they're a gaggle of vindictive crybabies with no sense of propriety.
Wulbren made his life there. For his sake, if nothing else, I'd like to see it survive.
With the sword of justice in one hand and the shield of self-righteousness in the other, we most certainly will.
I'd tell you to write, but I never check the post.
They have runepowder. They have motive. We have to stop them.
Barcus, Wulbren wants nothing to do with you. He made that clear.
Why are you so down? You should be celebrating my good deeds.
Wulbren and the Ironhand Gnomes are planning something dreadful in the city.
I'll be seeing you at your camp.
It isn't the first time, and I'm sure it won't be the last. But I won't let him hurt anyone - or himself.
Goodbye, Barcus.
That sounds... slimy. But never mind your distasteful predilections. We need to talk about Wulbren.
To saving the city - and my fool of a friend.
A pity Wulbren isn't here. You two would've gotten on like a house on fire, I think.

EditorData.NodeContext: A little funny, a litlte sad. Wulbren is dead.

Text.Value: You'll what? Tie me to a windmill? Enslave me in the Underdark? Smack me upside the head? I assure you, circumstance has beaten you to it.
Good riddance.
It seems we'll have our hands full in Baldur's Gate.
Leave it to me, Barcus. You've proven you aren't able for this kind of thing.
I was preoccupied defeating Ketheric Thorm.
Here I am. What do you want?
A job like you're describing isn't easy - what makes you think they're serious?
How can you be sure?
Knowing when to ask for help is a sign of wisdom, not weakness.
We don't need to say goodbye just yet. You're welcome at camp.
Is this just because Wulbren rejected you?
The city has more important concerns than a bunch of ne'er-do-wells with a grudge.
The city has more important concerns than a bunch of gnomes with a grudge.
Oh, forget about that. Wulbren and the Ironhand Gnomes are planning something dreadful in the city.
I'm not one for parties on the best of days. And today... is not the best of days.
Unfortunately for evil, it has you to worry about. Look after the city - it's an awful place, but it's home.
If I have to hear the name 'Wulbren' one more time...
I'm sorry I couldn't find your friend Wulbren.
Not quite. I didn't get this parasite out of my head.
A fellow knows when it's time to go his own way. We've had an interesting run of it, but it's time I whence'd my way back home.
Who? Oh - right. Well, forget about that magungus. We have more important things to worry about. Like Wulbren.
We're not out of the woods yet. It seems evil is on its way to Baldur's Gate.
Well, if you turn into a mind flayer, I'll be sure to tell people you were a decent sort, pre-tentacle.
Until, if ever, we meet again.

EditorData.NodeContext: A little sadly, a final farewell.

Text.Value: So. You did it. Cleared the tower. Killed the villain. Everything you said you'd do.

EditorData.InternalNodeContext: NEEDS FLAG: Wulbren is not saved, regardless of player having met him.
EditorData.NodeContext: Slightly verklempt. He's having a nice moment with us but is still grieving his friend.

Text.Value: But it doesn't do to remain smackd. We fall, we moan, then we rise to annoy our enemies once more.
Erm. I... I'll say my goodbyes now. You were - that is, it was... So long.

EditorData.NodeContext: Barcus is trying to have a heartfelt goodbye with the player but is very awkward.

Text.Value: I was taking a little holiday in the mind flayer colony downstairs.
You're tired from your exertions. Who could blame you? Have a smoke, a wash - or a polish, as it were - and let's regroup when you're more yourself.
You're tired from your exertions. Who could blame you? Have a smoke, a wash, and a cup of tea, and let's regroup when you're more yourself.
You helped me in this gods-awful quagmire; when we're back in the city, I'll be fully in my element once more.
Heh. As you say.

EditorData.NodeContext: Player has said 'good riddance' but Barcus doesn't take it pesonally. He waves goodbye.

Text.Value: Wulbren is... dead. Far before his time. Mourning him will be... well, it'll be the work of a lifetime.

Synopsis: He's a bit mopey but is very much wanting to stick by Wulbren's side despite being mistreated by him. He doesn't know what's happening next but he knows Wulbren has a plan. So that's something.
